{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532375"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:25:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:25:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14672"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14672"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.34,0.34,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57901"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7365"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14672"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43360"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1340"},{"type":"tags","id":"2774"},{"type":"tags","id":"4853"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43559"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57901"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 84-year-old man is admitted to hospital following a fall at home. He tripped on a rug while walking to answer his telephone. He has fallen three times in the past year. His medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes, osteoarthritis of both knees, bilateral hearing impairment (untreated), and mild cognitive impairment. His medications include metformin, perindopril, amlodipine, paracetamol, and vitamin D. He lives alone and uses a walking stick. His daughter reports he frequently misses conversations and turns the television volume very high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears frail but alert. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 138/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. He has difficulty following conversation without face-to-face contact. His gait is slow but steady with a walking stick.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains how treating hearing impairment could reduce his falls risk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced cognitive load allowing better attention","Improved balance through better vestibular function","Enhanced awareness of environmental hazards","Better response to verbal warnings","Increased confidence in social situations"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with multiple falls risk factors including age, polypharmacy, cognitive impairment, mobility issues, and untreated hearing impairment. Understanding how hearing impairment contributes to falls risk is crucial for comprehensive falls prevention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImproved balance through better vestibular function\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism by which treating hearing impairment reduces falls risk. The inner ear\u0027s vestibular system is closely integrated with auditory function. Hearing aids improve spatial awareness and environmental sound perception, which are essential for maintaining balance and postural stability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced cognitive load allowing better attention\u003C/strong\u003E is a contributing factor but not the primary mechanism. While hearing aids do reduce the mental effort required for listening, allowing more cognitive resources for other tasks, this is secondary to the direct vestibular effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced awareness of environmental hazards\u003C/strong\u003E through better hearing is beneficial but is not the main mechanism by which hearing aids reduce falls risk. While improved awareness of surroundings is helpful, the vestibular connection is more significant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetter response to verbal warnings\u003C/strong\u003E may help prevent some falls but is not the primary mechanism. While being able to hear warnings is important, most falls occur without prior verbal warning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased confidence in social situations\u003C/strong\u003E, while important for overall quality of life and reducing social isolation, is not directly related to the mechanical process of falls prevention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional benefits of hearing aid use include improved social engagement (reducing isolation and depression risk) and better overall function in daily activities. Studies have shown that older adults with treated hearing impairment have significantly lower falls rates compared to those with untreated hearing loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hearing impairment is an independent risk factor for falls in older adults, with treatment reducing falls risk by improving spatial awareness and balance.","Hearing aids improve social engagement and reduce cognitive load, allowing better attention to environmental hazards.","A comprehensive falls assessment should include evaluation of sensory impairments including hearing."],"references":["Kamil RJ, Betz J, Powers BB, et al. Association of Hearing Impairment With Incident Frailty and Falls in Older Adults. J Aging Health. 2016;28(4):644-660. doi:10.1177/0898264315608730. Available online at ; https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5644033/","Carpenter MG, Campos JL. The effects of hearing loss on balance: a critical review. Ear and hearing. 2020 Nov 1;41:107S-19S. Available online at ; https://journals.lww.com/ear-hearing/fulltext/2020/11001/the_effects_of_hearing_loss_on_balance__a_critical.12.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43360"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14672"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43360"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-27T22:56:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T22:57:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7365"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57901"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"